'''Alice Davis Marks Menken''' (August 4, 1870 – March 23, 1936) was a Jewish American known for her social work, particularly with female Jewish immigrant juvenile delinquency.

== Early life and career ==

Alice Davis Marks{{sfn|Klapper|2005|p=252}} was born in New York City on August 4, 1870, to Michael Marks and Miriam (Maduro Peixotto) Davis, the third of  their seven children. Both the Davis and  Peixotto families were distinguished [[Sephardic]] families long resident in New York City. Her family was active in their Manhattan temple, [[Congregation Shearith Israel]], where her great-grandfather, Moses Levi Maduro Peixotto, had been one of its first [[hazzan|cantors]].{{sfn|Herman|2009}} In her youth, Davis Menken attended the [[Gardner School for Girls|Gardner Institute]] and the [[New York School for Community Workers]].{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}} On October 17, 1893, she married Mortimer Morange Menken, an attorney{{sfn|Herman|2009}} and descendant of Rabbi [[Gershom Seixas]].{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}} Their only son, Harold Davis Menken, was born two years later.{{sfn|Herman|2009}} She served in the [[Women's Motor Corps]] during [[World War I]].{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}}

Davis Menken became known for her social work. She was an active member of the [[National Council of Jewish Women]], a trustee of the [[Federation of Jewish Philanthropies]] and Women's Branch of [[Union of Orthodox Jewish Congregations]], and 27-year sisterhood president of her temple, Shearith Israel (1901–1928).{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}} She co-founded the Shearith Israel Sisterhood in 1896.{{sfn|Herman|2009}} In 1905 she was a member of the [[Committee of Fourteen]].<ref name=mac>{{cite book|last1=Mackey|first1=Thomas C.|title=Pursuing johns : criminal law reform, defending character, and New York City's Committee of Fourteen, 1920-1930|date=2005|publisher=Ohio state university press|location=Columbus (Ohio)|isbn=0814209882|page=111}}</ref> Davis Menken began her career in social relief work at the sisterhood's [[settlement house|settlement]] Neighborhood House, which worked with the surrounding Jewish immigrant community, especially those who arrived in 1908 to escape the [[Ottoman Empire]]. This experience led to her interest in helping to stem increased [[juvenile delinquency]] in female Jewish immigrant populations.{{sfn|Herman|2009}} Davis Menken founded the [[Jewish Board of Family and Children's Services|Jewish Board of Guardians]] in 1907, which increased delinquent supervision after probation to three years. In 1908, she started a sisterhood committee to help the [[New York City Probation Department]] in the [[Women's Night Court]], which helped Jewish women in the court until the court was dissolved eleven years later.{{sfn|Herman|2009}} She later started the [[Jewish Big Sister Movement]].{{sfn|Klapper|2005|p=252}}

She was president of the [[Society for Political Study]] from 1911 to 1913, and worked as a trustee with the [[Institute for Instruction of Deaf Mutes]], and as a director of the [[Florence Crittendon League]].{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}} As an expert on [[prison reform]], New York Governor [[Al Smith|Alfred Smith]] appointed her to the [[New York State Reformatory for Women]] board of managers in 1920, and she also sat on the [[National Committee on Prisons and Prison Labor]].{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}} Davis Menken authored several books pertaining to women's social welfare,{{sfn|Klapper|2005|p=252}} including a book on prison reform.{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}} She was also a member of the Republican Party, [[Women's City Club of New York|Women's City Club]], and the [[National Probation Association]].{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}} Her husband died January 1, 1930.{{sfn|NYT|1930}}

Davis Menken died March 23, 1936{{sfn|Rogow|1993|p=232}} in her New York City Hotel Westover apartment.{{sfn|NYT|1936}}

== Selected works ==

* ''Hints for Meeting the Problem of Maladjusted Youth: A Study in Social Work for Beginners'' (1922){{sfn|Herman|2009}}
* "The Rehabilitation of the Morally Handicapped." ''Journal of the American Institute of Criminal Law and Criminology'' 16 (May 1924): 147–154.{{sfn|Herman|2009}}
* ''On the Side of Mercy: Problems in Social Readjustment'' (1933){{sfn|Herman|2009}}

